        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The sons named as heads of houses are three, viz. Jehieli (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and his sons, Zetham and Joel. Those who think that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " carries with it the meaning that Jehieli, Zetham, and Joel were all three brothers, can, in point of fact, plausibly reduce this verse to their shape. For the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "yod",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not welcome at the end of the name ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Jehieli",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here, might be read the conjunction ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "vau",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in both instances in which it occurs. The reading would then run thus: \"Jehiel and the sons of Jehiel, both Zetham and Joel his brother.\" 1 Chronicles 26:21",
        "children": []
